body:
ref https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/issues/30609#issuecomment-606121355

Cythonizing files with 0.29.14 and Python 3.8 produces warnings such as the following:

```sh
pandas/io/sas/sas.c:20457:3: error: 'tp_print' is deprecated [-Werror,-Wdeprecated-declarations]
  0, /*tp_print*/
  ^
/Users/williamayd/miniconda3/envs/py38/include/python3.8/cpython/object.h:260:5: note: 'tp_print' has been explicitly marked deprecated here
    Py_DEPRECATED(3.8) int (*tp_print)(PyObject *, FILE *, int);
    ^
/Users/williamayd/miniconda3/envs/py38/include/python3.8/pyport.h:515:54: note: expanded from macro 'Py_DEPRECATED'
#define Py_DEPRECATED(VERSION_UNUSED) __attribute__((__deprecated__))
                                                     ^
5 errors generated.
```

These did not appear in Cython 0.29.13. I *think* this may have to do with changes introduced in  #3201

comment_data.body:
Yes, this is due to #3201.

Apparently, these warnings can be silenced, at least in gcc:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13459602/how-can-i-get-rid-of-deprecated-warnings-in-deprecated-functions-in-gcc/13459924#13459924

Failing that, it seems that at least someone may end up being unhappy here – whoever doesn't want to see deprecation warnings or whoever doesn't want to see "missing initialiser" warnings.

This whole thing feels a bit insane to me…

Cool thanks for the info! Actually I was bisecting yesterday and didn't see the warnings as introduced by that. It's possible I made a mistake on bisect, but at the same time could be a red herring. Will investigate further and post back

@scoder so reading through the issues, was the main reason to add the initializer in the first place to allow files that were cythonized on say 3.7 and earlier to still be compilable in a 3.8 environment without warning?

> was the main reason to add the initializer…

Well, yes. The field is still there, so you get a warning if you don't initialise it. And since it is deprecated, you get a warning that you're accessing a deprecated field if you initialise it. Lovely.

Sorry if this is a naive question and I'm just missing something, but is there a way to bracket the field access with an `#ifdef`/`#if` to avoid having that usage show up on versions where the warning would appear?

> Sorry if this is a naive question and I'm just missing something, but is there a way to bracket the field access with an `#ifdef`/`#if` to avoid having that usage show up on versions where the warning would appear?

It's already bracketed like that to stop it on versions where the field definitely doesn't exist. The trouble is on the intermediate versions where the field exists but is marked deprecated:

* Don't initialize the field and you get a warning about not initializing the field.
* initialize the field and you get a warning that it's deprecated.

You could locally play with compiler pragmas to turn the warning off, but unfortunately that doesn't quite fit naturally with how Cython generates this code.

In Python 3.9, this issue with `tp_print` make some packages impossible to install. In my CI tests, all environments with Python 3.9 have this error:
```
    astroscrappy/astroscrappy.c: In function ‘__Pyx_modinit_type_init_code’:
    astroscrappy/astroscrappy.c:26822:25: error: ‘PyTypeObject {aka struct _typeobject}’ has no member named ‘tp_print’
       __pyx_type___pyx_array.tp_print = 0;
                             ^
    astroscrappy/astroscrappy.c:26827:31: error: ‘PyTypeObject {aka struct _typeobject}’ has no member named ‘tp_print’
       __pyx_type___pyx_MemviewEnum.tp_print = 0;
                                   ^
    astroscrappy/astroscrappy.c:26842:30: error: ‘PyTypeObject {aka struct _typeobject}’ has no member named ‘tp_print’
       __pyx_type___pyx_memoryview.tp_print = 0;
                                  ^
    astroscrappy/astroscrappy.c:26855:35: error: ‘PyTypeObject {aka struct _typeobject}’ has no member named ‘tp_print’
       __pyx_type___pyx_memoryviewslice.tp_print = 0;
                                       ^
    error: command '/usr/bin/gcc' failed with exit code 1
```
    
This occur when the program try to install `astroscrappy`, that is a package built using Cython. Same problem reported on https://github.com/astropy/ccdproc/issues/752 and https://github.com/astropy/astroscrappy/issues/55

@juliotux what version of cython are you using in your CI? Anything from 0.29.14 and later should not be showing that error. Just to be clear: astrocrappy offers no binary wheels, only source distributions, so every install uses cython to compile the code to c. You should ensure you are using the latest release of cython in your CI (0.29.21 right now).

@mattip even when forcing Cython to 0.29.21 this problem happens. Please, take a look on this Travis job: [travis-ci](https://travis-ci.com/github/sparc4-dev/astropop/jobs/474960994#L223)
On line 223 I explicit print the system Cython version and on line 258 I ensure tox is installing the correct Cython version.
Ahh, I see. The source tarball on PyPI includes the processed C file from the pyx file, and the first line says `/* Generated by Cython 0.29.2 */`. So they need to make a new release.
I [requested they update the cython version](https://github.com/astropy/astroscrappy/issues/50#issuecomment-766903218) on an open issue about a new release of astrocrappy

title: Cython 0.29.14 and Py38 generates warnings for tp_print
